text: So, you know, there are, I think, some analogs in traditional factor investing to what goes on in the equity option space. So, for example, the most obvious one is, you know, option selling strategies for income certainly are expressions of a carry style, right? They are in a predefined rate of income if there's no move in the underlying securities. They see that income slowly eroded if the underlying is starting to move around a lot. And similarly, strategies that sell VIX futures like XIV, for example, before it blew up in February of last year, earn carry from the typical upward sloping shape of the term structure of implied volatility, effectively generating compensation for taking the risk of loss in a volatility spike. That's a very clear analog, I think. You know, outside of that, I think that you see much less of the language of style premium broadly applied to volatility markets. There are some elements of momentum. There's a lot of momentum and mean reversion in volatility. In particular, volatility over long periods of time is and has to be mean reverting. And so there's people who think about the time dynamics of that. But over short periods of time, it may or may not be true. But on the point about, you know, the Star Wars framework, of course, that's a facetious word to some extent. But, you know, the silly nerd analogy being that we're all quants after all, is that relative value strategies really sort of, aren't really the same as the relative value strategies. Right. And so, you know, I think that's a really interesting point. I mean, end users of derivatives do things in big herds, and they typically have very large size relative to the absolute return community. And they're very sticky. Right. So just take the example of, say, the last five or six years, you know, when the huge pension funds of the world start to allocate a meaningful part of their portfolio to call overwriting and equity replacement via put selling. Right. And they all do it in very similar benchmark ways in the same types of one month near the money S&P options in very, very big size. It creates a big disturbance in the force. It creates just this huge congestion in one small piece of the overall options market, creates really steep term structures. Market makers get stuffed with short term options. They don't have the risk limits to hold. And the community, the relative value community's job is really to. To distribute that risk much more broadly throughout the ecosystem, relieve the congestion caused by very heavy benchmarking and very, very large sizes relative to the size of the market in that particular type of trade that those end users are doing and try to create a nice risk reward profile and get paid to provide the liquidity to that to that market. So really, that's what we're talking about. Really, end users of options. When you see that type of behavior. Tends to be very, very impactful in a particular part of the market that needs someone on the other side to warehouse the basis risk and to distribute that risk.
